 This method is also applied to optimization, which is suitable for processing
 optimization problems of multi-dimensional space.
 When searching for the minimum value of a multi-dimensional function, the
 MC will first generate random points in the parameter space.
 Next, we can estimate which parameter regions have lower values and further
 narrow these regions with further random points.
 By repeating the same steps, we can numerically approximate the true minimum
 value.
 In the case of PDF global fit, the parameters associated with the best-fit
 PDFs are the minimum point we want to approach.
 The Hessian method is a method of finding the local minimum of a function
 using second-order Taylor expansion.
 The relationship between the minimum value of a convex function and the
 point near it can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(x+\Delta x)=f(x)+f'\Delta x+\Delta xH(x)\Delta x+O(\Delta x^{3})
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Where H(x) contains the contribution of the second-order differential, which
 we call the Hessian matrix.
 We rewrite this relationship to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f'(x+\Delta x)=\frac{f(x+\Delta x)-f(x)}{\Delta x}=f'(x)+H(x)\Delta x
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This relationship shows that we can use the first-order derivative and second-or
der derivative of a point in the parameter space to get the first-order
 derivative of any nearby point.
 Since the first-order derivative of local minimum is 0 and the second-order
 derivative of which is positive.
 Finding the local minimum nearby a point requires that the Hessian matrix
 be positive and RHS is 0, then we get the vector toward the local minimum
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x=-H(x)^{-1}f'(x)$
\end_inset

.
 In practice, the high-order terms of Taylor expansion are not negligible
 for points far from the local minimum, so the points we find have deviation
 from the real local minimum.
 However, we can constantly approach the real local minimum by repeating
 the searching process.
 Steps of the Hessian method are as following: from the initial point, investiga
tes other points near the point to estimate the first-order derivative and
 Hessian matrix, then moves to 
\begin_inset Formula $x+\Delta x$
\end_inset

, and then repeats the same process until the real local minimum (the first-orde
r derivative disappear).
